<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: EDUCATION: RENEWAL OF PARCEL TAX DISCUSSED BY SCHOOL OFFICIALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Santa Monica-Malibu Unified school officials are weighing whether to renew a 
parcel tax in the two cities. 
</P>
<P>
 A panel of local residents, business people and teachers are evaluating the 
$58-per-parcel tax, on the books since 1988 and scheduled to expire in June of 
next year. Arthur Cohen, the district's finance director, said the committee 
could recommend increasing the tax or keeping it at the current rate. 
</P>
<P>
 By April of this year, the school board will decide whether to place the 
parcel tax on the November ballot. The tax generates about $1.8 million 
annually, Cohen said. The money helps pay for books, insurance, hiring teachers 
and other operational costs. 
</P>
