<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SANTA MONICA; ST. JOHN'S TO GIVE EX-WORKERS JOB PRIORITY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KATHLEEN KELLEHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After hearing complaints from employees, administrators at St. John's Hospital 
and Health Center have modified their agreement with the 1,750 workers who lost 
their jobs Feb. 7 because of the facility's earthquake damage. 
</P>
<P>
 Bruce Lamoureux, chief operating officer for St. John's Hospital, told 
employees at a Sunday farewell gathering that they would be given priority for 
available jobs over other applicants when the hospital reopens. Also, he said, 
St. John's employees who are rehired would retain their seniority. 
</P>
<P>
 Neither provision had been part of the employee agreement, according to 
Lamoureux. 
</P>
<P>
 The news was loudly applauded by a crowd of about 300. The crowd included some 
of the 250 employees retained for outpatient services as well as severed 
employees, some of whom have found new jobs and others who have not. 
</P>
<P>
 One who lost her job, Donni Esposti, a care coordinator with the hospital for 
28 years, said she didn't think the hospital had any choice but to do what it 
did. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's never going to be the same," she said. "We're going to go down in beds. 
I'm sorry some of us lost our jobs, but we can reapply. I'm starting a new job 
Monday in home care." 
</P>
<P>
 At the employee gathering, where hot dogs, popcorn, nachos, Cokes and cookies 
were served, former colleagues embraced one another and talked about job 
prospects and mulling over the latest conciliatory move by the administrators 
of a hospital most called "a family." 
</P>
<P>
 Another former employee, who was nearly four months pregnant and carried her 
husband on her St. John's health care plan, worried about paying her health 
insurance premium after the hospital stops paying it at the end of April. 
</P>
<P>
 The Sunday employees' gathering came a day after St. John's held another party 
for the public. There, hospital administrators and Santa Monica Mayor Judy Abdo 
assured those in attendance that the hospital would be doing business on an 
outpatient basis immediately and would eventually build a "better" care center 
for the community of Santa Monica. KATHLEEN KELLEHER 
</P>
</TEXT>
