<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: UNIVERSAL CITY; 
COMPROMISE OFFERED ON MCA COMPLEX SUBWAY STOP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City transit officials have proposed a compromise for the Universal City Metro 
Rail station that would preserve the planned Lankershim Boulevard site but 
better serve the MCA entertainment complex, potentially satisfying key demands 
by the multimedia company and county transportation planners. 
</P>
<P>
 MCA has pushed hard to move the subway station to the doorstep of its 
Universal Studios and CityWalk complex -- a proposal resisted by county 
transportation planners as being too costly and time-consuming. 
</P>
<P>
 But city analysts say in a report that the new Red Line station could remain 
on Lankershim but should include an entrance on the Universal Studios lot up 
the hill, with shuttle service between the gates and the station. Access to the 
entertainment center would therefore be improved without the added delays and 
costs of moving the station directly onto the Universal Studios lot, as MCA has 
lobbied for. 
</P>
<P>
 Both MCA executives and officials of the county Metropolitan Transportation 
Authority said Wednesday that the proposal appears workable, fueling hope that 
the long-running disagreement between MCA and the transit agency over station 
location could be near an end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
