IMMUNOLOGIST IS NAMED TO HEAD AIDS RESEARCH PROGRAMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A prominent immunologist was named Wednesday to head the AIDS research 
programs at the National Institutes of Health. 
</P>
<P>
 Dr. William Paul, best known for his discovery of a key immune system molecule 
that is attacked by the AIDS virus, will head the NIH's Office of AIDS 
Research. He was named to the post by Dr. Harold Varmus, the director of the 
NIH. 
</P>
<P>
 Congress, under pressure from AIDS activists, last spring reorganized the 
office, giving it more personnel and power to direct federally funded research 
into the viral plague. 
